The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long before he gets here.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges will probably come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS that send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, has already stated that there is no longer room in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant decrease in prices to which the classical operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
There is no need to look too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
After only half a year, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to concentrate on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large expenses in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low expenses - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages which however, is often counteracted with the offer of more tight services.
So, for example, Tesco mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half cheaper than the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a good hit also betting on a nothing trivial goal group.
This operator is specifically aimed at man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – it’s the operator he likes and can be trusted,” says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works for this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if such a concept as that of Poland could engage in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of the service offer is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be some virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region,” Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told mobil.cz by phone.
He indirectly said that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to move forward in the meetings," said the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe better times are flashing.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has approached us with any complex and serious project in this field," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, spokesman for Telefónica O2, told mobil.cz.
Other operators are concerned with the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2's opinion, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to be developed."
He adds: “In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that it would be possible to study in such a short horizon.
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We consider it to be the greatest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a drop in prices and with it, a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier to enter the competition?
When operators want to achieve something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of this is the grip when it emerged U:fon.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is attested by publicly available information on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "In addition, it is not long ago that the competitive environment in the mobile market was opened to a fourth operator.
As far as the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is only natural that the entry of another player into the market would be very demanding for him and, above all, for his services."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in trade tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, she expressed her typical stance on this issue.
The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was closed.
To date no agreement has been concluded as the offer of potential stakeholders was rather not interesting enough for the classical operators," added Kristián Chalupa, of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS Foreign Relations department, to our question.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers it is more than a consideration, apart from that they must observe that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Overseas, where virtual operators operate normally, we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the lower prices of mobile phone services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the lowering of prices are not in the interest of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Really the dramatic shock in this whole case lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether this is really a coincidence offers itself.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at the gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
"The Office has found no signs of unfair competition in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position and therefore do not have a corresponding increase in liability in their actions in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as well as telecommunication regulators," Chalupa added to his response.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of conflict.
There is obviously a relevant market analysis by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to emerge, the agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise strikingly similarly.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they clash with many similar impediments.
Carrying responsibility on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in the telecommunications field from which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands on this whole matter.
We have already met him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law for the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s competition in the field of commercial tenders was not put into effect recently, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know this perfectly, but it is clear that their interests lie elsewhere.
All is well when no one is looking.
At the same time, a pseudo-virtual operator that already exists in Czech cellular networks is still functioning unnoticed.
They are companies that put their own prices to mobile phone services that, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a select few get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions at all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as the ones you cite were discovered, we could talk about a breach in the terms of the contract that could translate into the end of the collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová responded to the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they obtain a not negligible profit and, at the same time - unlike the authentic virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible so much percent of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card of their phone is not in their name so they cannot have it absolutely as a normal customer of the operators.
Precisely this is what should seem to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> minimally strange.
In addition, a new question for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS appears.
If mobile operators turn their eyes on this type of procedure, why do they block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has enough competence to discover this type of activities and if it is not going to want it should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive?
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant decrease in the prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually every country where the virtual operator emerged, the classical operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this irruption.
The arguments used by these were practically all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have intervened at the moment and in none of the cases defended the operators but their customers.
Whether formal measures or informal pressure resulted in the emergence of the first virtual operator and with it began to emerge others.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body spends this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of powers in these cases suits them.
But let us not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile market is likely to start moving again.
If one of the operators allows a virtual mobile operator to enter, it will be difficult for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
