Hidden by the expansion of the theme park of Greater Orlando, a few kilometers from the bright, noisy and colossal city, lies a quiet village, where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are very evident.
Eatonville, the first fully black-inhabited city incorporated into the country and childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 men of color, 300 good swimmers, many guavas, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Fair in Eatonville to pay tribute to Mrs. Hurston, Harlem’s most famous Renaissance writer.
And yet, in many ways, the city she described – making it also a tourist stop by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Federal Writers’ Project of the Depression Season – remains a place apart.
The city remains independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Mrs. Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their true ideas with the white man, who "knows so little about us and doesn't know what is being lost."
