Talking Sleepy
Some kids talk at night.
I do not mean those who wake up very smart telling us something that has happened the day before, but children who talk while asleep.
The first time it happens, you might be scared, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign disturbance of sleep that is called sleep apnea.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one person has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in a lifetime for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal bedwetting or sleepwalking, but it does not have to be so.
As we have already mentioned before, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitation.
In any case, it is a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or quite the opposite (screams, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him exit in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What you can do is take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain internal calm.
This will allow the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the somnilochias appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything of what has happened.
Useful Advice
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even though he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore he is resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes it would be advisable to consult or find out what generates so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common), do not be tempted to interrogate him to get information.
You will achieve nothing, because when you are asleep you are not conscious enough to organize your thought.
Besides, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, so be very careful how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes children to be anxious.
In short, don’t worry, it’s not a bad thing, it’s an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
