Interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
Above all, it regained the public confidence that had been seriously hesitated by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated with the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this tragedy and the discontent of the public, in February 1994 the Government of Canada conducted a public survey, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations so that such a disaster would not occur again.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his report, certain provinces then created a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
“In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec,” says Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and much work over the years that followed, we have regained the public’s trust,” he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population had now confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that "confidence is an extremely fragile thing."
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn’t know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
So we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know it and when a serious disease can emanate from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we institute exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that allow the presence of the virus and not antibodies against the virus to be detected directly in the blood of donors, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nucleid acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
This substantially reduces the risk of certain donors being infected unknowingly and not being able to detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“That means we’ll have to distribute 12 million blood products before anyone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to regain health without worries," says the head of management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continues before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
" Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Because anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has an impact on the blood donor network, which on average comprises only 3 per cent of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All persons in good health, 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria can still donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But members of this donor network need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since current life is very rampant, we rarely find time to spend an hour to donate her blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
“We celebrated a few weeks ago, the bench placement of our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood and we are expected to draw more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts early next year,” says Dr. Décary who describes this cord blood-taking program as very popular.
“Many moms are disappointed that they can’t enjoy this,” as Héma-Québec doesn’t have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
