Very soon, on October 8, the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing frauds of significant harm, of business mode, continuously and in an organized way in addition to other crimes, including the falsification of documents.
According to the Office of the Prosecutor, they used for their own purposes the funds obtained in public tenders, often justifying the fulfillment of the tasks with false invoices.
The public funds and that of the municipalities - in total about 65 million HUF - stopped partly in the treasury of the organization Fiatal Baloldal and partly in the pockets of private individuals.
The method, which was also disclosed by the researchers, was to justify the collection of the funds obtained in public tenders with false invoices behind which there was no actual execution, the various associations never fulfilled their assumed obligations.
According to the prosecution, most of the bills were false.
To do this they obtained the booklets in the market of the District of Józsefváros and the circular seals were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question of which company should make the counterfeit invoice was decided among others on that tour of the Upper Balaton Region where János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for his consumption and these served as a model to prepare the invoices that they presented, among others, in the competitions of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, in the Ministry of Social and Labor Affairs, as well as in the City Council of the Capital.
These invoices were mostly signed by István Lados and his accomplice András <0xC5><0x90>ri, who according to our information rather wrote the necessary reports to obtain the public grants.
During one of his "study trips" Lados chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomic center provided food for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However - according to the manager of the center - so many people do not fit at once in that place.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Foundation - later called Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
For a hostel in the town of Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, yet on the bill there were one hundred and thirty people.
But the fancy invoice makers also exaggerated when they pointed to the Pigal Kft. gastronomic center because in its bookstore - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért and Hoppá.
Gy<0xC5><0x91>z<0xC5><0x91> Farkas, the company’s manager, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned by the prosecution and was shown the invoices, he already knew they were fake documents.
"On the stamp our company name and NIF appeared in the wrong place."
He added: in addition to the formal problems, it was also not agreed that according to the bill a hundred people were accommodated, since they have only eleven rooms in which not so many people can fit.
In addition, meals were also included in the bill, while the restaurant has not worked for a long time.
The enthusiastic invoice makers were also not informed that the chosen travel agency in Budapest exclusively organizes trips abroad, so that in the invoice for payment in cash they foolishly indicated as a service a trip within Hungary, which also did not coincide with the practice of issuing invoices of the agency.
In addition – as was known during the investigation – they included in the document VAT as well, despite the fact that travel outside the territory of the European Union was exempt from tax.
Among other things, the VAT measure was also incorrect in the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. for the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért foundation, since the services of that company are not charged with a 25 but only with 15 percent VAT, in addition the hotel employees only extended invoices made by machine but the invoice was manual.
In addition the "senders" have made other errors also, as in the case of a company in which they put on the bill as activity realized the road transport to which - it is known during the investigations of the prosecution - does not the company founded as investment consultant.
Also due to formal differences - inadequate format of the invoice, false stamp - it was found that the invoices issued for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont are false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued those invoices.
The counterfeiters also did not pay attention to the fact that when the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in the process of liquidation, so the person in charge of the liquidation process - according to our information - denied having issued such a document.
They consciously sent out the invoices
