Psychology of Overlapping: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University have discovered the neurological-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
The scientists attempted to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other participated in an auction and in the meantime the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment were examined by the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system.
In both games the participants could win money, but during the auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the nervous system’s “self-reward” mechanism.
Thus, according to the scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the real value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 in prize money.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the members of the group lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, checking the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For until now they explained the phenomena of auctions solely with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University's faculty of economics.
Hepatitis: When should I go to the doctor?
Some 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses in dependence on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vagina mood, saliva).
It is advisable for travelers to protect themselves with vaccines against the viruses A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by a poor general state, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that appear on the skin and on the white of the eyes jaundice, the excrement becomes clear, the urine dark in color and the healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year one million people die in the world from liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most severe forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to calculations, only one in ten infected receives drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Therefore, premature recognition, systematic medical monitoring is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory check-up as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease has cure if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the contagion and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt less to those who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent research, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed religious belief in how it influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
As part of this unique experiment, they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it was verified that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
This experiment is the first in a series of investigations in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate alongside academics.
The analysis took place as follows; they fixed a sparkling instrument to the left hand of the patient, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their gaze on two paintings; the 17th-century Virgin Mary by Sassoferrato and Leonardo da Vinci’s 15th-century Lady of the Hermine.
The researchers hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo’s oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a reassuring effect.
The patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving in that period 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
The Catholics said that looking at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "they were reassured and in their heart reigned peace."
When looking at the religious-themed painting, they felt 12 percent less pain than when looking at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for which they feel very positively, as for a mother or a father," - said the psychologist.
