You are what you say about yourself
On its tenth birthday Google can say: you can find it both in people’s pockets and in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, which doctors they visit and what interests them.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who make a parallel with the Orwelian vision do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to collect as much personal data about its users as possible, and this is necessary to be able to meet the original goals of Google’s founders: “Let’s gather all the information of the world in one system!”
According to the leader of Google, the company even after ten years of work that turned the world upside down is still in the initial phase of the effort to be able to process all the information.
To the question of what will happen five years from now, Schmidt said: “I would like Google to be able to answer questions like ‘What to do tomorrow?’ or ‘What would be the job that would suit me best?’ – however, software won’t be able to answer seemingly simple questions as long as there isn’t enough user information.
Not all Internet users are aware that while browsing the Web the searched keywords, IP addresses and pages they visited at the end of the search are accurately stored.
Thanks for example to Personalized Search that debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can re-check what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches -in this same logic will be based on the Recommendations, on which the system will offer us products and services based on the preferences previously defined and stored.
What will happen if they take advantage of my data against myself, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who care about seeing the information monopoly of Google.
In most cases it is rather the potential represented by the company that can be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, yearning for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that not only preserve, but in justifiable cases also cede to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most debated example of recent times was perhaps the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google handed over to the Brazilian government the information from its website, called Orkut, to identify pedophiles.
Internet users who care about people’s rights, on the other hand, were relieved in May when the company, together with the EFF, an organization for the defense of electronic rights, successfully demonstrated before the court that it was right in its litigation with the FBI: according to the sentence, Google cannot be forced, through any of the points of the constitution to provide any kind of information requested in secret by the FBI.
(At the same time the federal government managed to get under the pretext of reinforcing the child protection law passed years ago, about fifty thousand Web addresses and about a thousand search phrases, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of Web pages and keywords of the last two months.)
The opinion on Google is quite contradictory: it is criticized by those who are afraid to provide their personal data because they think that their privacy, their private life is harmed by starting to use Google’s services, and they rebel against it as against the multinational companies of conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, netizens and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "avant-garde corporation", not so its rival, Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as conqueror of the World, no matter how much they both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for their applications, the code is open and the free program package, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks see with precision the very problematic relationship between people’s rights and the Internet that was produced precisely by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, about intentionally leaving footprints behind us and taking advantage of available communication channels, and while the measurements of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: show ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Shanghai, and can even combine them with other services, such as Twitter or last.fm that offers a list of their music habits, then you can include them in a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, you can also have a blog, in which automatically appear the latest photo galleries that are stored on the Pilick.
We can know numerous cases from which it turns out that for example the bride, when she sees the flow of photos the next morning of common friends, finds out who spent the night before her fraudulent boyfriend or they can fire the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion on his blog about the management of the company: one thing is for sure, the definition of private life was completely revalued.
A person’s “online” life is what she shows of herself – this is the definition that lurks behind the behavior of today’s youth.
And the one who wants to hide something, or at least wants to dodge Google’s monopoly, can do so (beginning for example with Scroogle that uses Google’s search system, but leaves no footprints).
There are many people who do not want to register on the collective pages to prevent them from being found, but you can replace the "online" applications of Google, from the text-writing software to the applications of image and news reading with alternative versions which do not connect with gigantic servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
The public expects almost openly the day when Google will show its true face.
The company with its current value of 156 billion dollars is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca-Cola (110 billion dollars), AdWords/AdSense advertising surfaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, while the services that are introduced more and more quickly also cause serious headaches to numerous other companies not only for the Microsoft, but also for Microsoft.
Critical observers, however, will find the contradictions alarming as well: for example, the top management strongly rejected the protest of employees after doubling the price of the company's nursery, considered too expensive the unlimited number of feeding of employees, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 the Chinese Google gave in to the pressure of the Chinese government and the company violated the moral information according to the agreement.
One of the company's internal regulations says that they will not announce any new service in advance, but only when it was already ready to operate, which if it is certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will be able to turn the World upside down: while some believe that the project of scanning and archiving of books and magazines from Google will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be cited by our Supreme Court with our own analysis of the United States.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database, will be able to provide a good raw material for writers of sci-fi works, the Scroogled, novel by the popular Cory Doctorow, describes in an Orwellian way that future, in which a man only of the data of Google can be described alarmingly well.
