The smart car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of obstacle sensors existing in nature?
Take bumblebees, for example.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the BR23C-type robotic car steering system imitating nature, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, chief technology officer of PR and development and research.
Composite eyes of bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees play an important role.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, the engineers used the laser length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at a 180-degree angle, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor of the vehicle that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning the wheels to the necessary extent.
Unlike any existing system today, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
“If this were not the case, the robot in the vehicle would not be able to react quickly enough to dodge obstacles,” says Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Lab and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should be done in a flash.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as possibility for the robot of the car the rotary movement and the acceleration in addition to the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the processing capacity of the data, much less the storage.
This device every second only needs to process a few input signals and react as appropriate.
There is no need to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No gigabyte or megabyte memory is needed.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately dodge obstacles, which according to Nissan calculations, within ten years will be able to be incorporated into mass-produced models.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, dodging existing obstacles in his way.
