The written version of the $700 billion financial bailout package law has been prepared to be implemented in several phases in order to buy bad loans from banks.
Half of the money will be spent in the first phase.
According to East Coast timetable during further consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement on the $700 billion total bailout package, after several days of discussion, Reuters reported.
We've made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic congressional chairwoman, saying the deal was only formalized in one document.
The commitment made on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Finance Minister, speaking about the outcome of the compromise stated: this program will work and will be efficient but other measures are needed. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving Wall Street, but turning the chariot of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets, i.e. Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington time (i.e. before 2 a.m. on Monday, according to Central European time), without causing a spectacular jump in the stock markets.
On the bill called the 2008 emergency bill for economic stabilization, the U.S. Congress will vote first on Monday, and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news of the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made overnight and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program is different from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend all $700 billion to buy low-quality credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, on this sum, the Finance Ministry will buy bonds with bad credit ratings and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president’s decision.
This program will be controlled by a special agency, in which the president of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion could be spent after a new congressional decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages and securities credit fund securities, in addition to other "poisonous" loans as well.
The purchase can be made in auctions or directly - informed competent people of the ministry.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the finance portfolio guarantees the worrying items, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson stated: the law secures the necessary financial means, which can even reach up to 700 billion dollars to meet the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it is the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some large financial institutions.
We do everything necessary to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it, he added.
On the other hand, the heads of the banks that are in trouble and waiting for the aid of the state can count on the official limitation of their compensation, which the American slang simply calls parachutes of gold.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and the limitations depend on the form of aid provided by the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys as part of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on gold parachutes, unless the bank’s failed boss retires.
By buying bad credits directly, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the bosses’ compensations are not exaggerated.
In addition to the above, the existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations refer only to new contracts to stimulate participation in the program.
This is the first case in U.S. history that a legal cap on CEOs’ incomes will be in place, said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the congressional commission responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the program, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, since in the end they will even be able to make profits with the transaction as soon as the economy recovers and with it the bank.
According to the bill, in the next five years the president will have to present to Congress a proposal on how to return to taxpayers the losses of the financial sector.
Of course, there were those on both sides who expressed their reservations regarding the project.
“This is not what American citizens have entrusted us with, that is, taxpayer dollars are not being protected,” Republican Congressman Darrell Issa said.
Ohio’s Democratic colleague Mary Kaptur said the measures were urged by those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices, the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose 1.1 percent from July 2008 and fell 3.9 percent from a year earlier.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose 0.7 percent from the previous month and 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial selling prices rose only to a minimal extent, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors rose minimally, by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The largest increase in price magnitude occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), primarily due to a 4.6 per cent monthly increase in bags and belts and a 2.5 per cent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemicals production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a price decrease in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 percent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
Prices for papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the other sectors of the processing industry, prices increased between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent an important weight within domestic trade, there was an increase of 0.3 percent in August, firstly as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from July 1.
In a comparison over a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal processing sector an increase of 13.2 percent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
A decrease in prices was recorded in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally, prices increased by 10.2 percent.
Prices of electricity, gas, heat and water surpassed last year's prices by 18.7 percent.
In the month of August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase ( 0.7 percent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices rose by 0.3 percent, while prices in the energy and intermediate sectors remained unchanged from the previous month.
In the month of August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods industries, a decline of 6.8 percent was recorded and in investment goods, 1.4 percent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 percent from the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in one month fell by 1.7 percent against the euro and by 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
