The European Summit for Equal Opportunities has started today in Paris, its host is France, which is also this year the President of the European Union.
Livia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party for Fidesz, in her message to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that affect gypsy children and it is also the biggest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European organisations for the protection of social rights.
Járóka - according to the press office of the group of Fidesz deputies in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, gypsies are left out of the labor market in the first place because of their low level of education.
"Most young Roma have not finished middle school and because of the poor quality of basic education, only a negligible part can obtain a university diploma."
Járóka further stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investing in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the MEP, these issues need to be widely raised among both Roma and non-Roma people.
For the earlier a Gypsy student starts school, the more likely he or she will be to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"The Roma, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to a quality education and ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education" - stressed Livia Járóka.
According to the MEP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to immediately accelerate the processes of school desegregation, for which the correct compliance with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is of fundamental importance.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer gypsy children the possibility that guarantees the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens" - demanded Járóka.
The aim of the European Summit on Equal Opportunities, which has been held annually since last year's Berlin meeting under the banner of the European Year of Equal Opportunities, is to ensure a unique forum for promoting the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
