MP3 Players Under Accusation Put Hearing at Risk
Listening to music at high volumes for a long period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
In a statement issued in Brussels, the European Commission cites the opinion of the Scientific Commission on Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risk (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
“From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day having the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity.”
“I am concerned that such a high number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and cell phones at a high acoustic level may unconsciously ruin their ears in an irremediable way,” says Meglena Kuneva.
“From the scientific evidence emerges a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What counts is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion, so that they are widely effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the large use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise that this causes.
“The scientists confirm that this is a matter of concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could eventually be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music and related devices.”
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100 dB, but concern increases as the hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as the reduction of levels and of the time of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that if users of portable music devices listen to high volume (more than 89 decibels) music for only 5 hours a week they exceed the limit currently in force concerning the maximum noise consented in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk permanent hearing loss after a period of 5 years.
It means that it affects 5-10% of users of such devices and the number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
