Students victims of expensive rent, up to 900 euros for a room
The rent market for college students is not aware of the crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants’ union, renting a single room could cost a student 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"the phenomenon has already assumed very serious characteristics to the point of excluding the right to study a large part of young people because of the very high costs that the family would have to bear - explains the head of the office studies of the Sunia, Laura Mariani - in these cities the strong demand has totally distorted the market to the point of triggering a process of generalized increase even for residents".
Apart from that in most cases the rental offers contain a series of violations: free type contracts, unregistered, without limit of canon, linked sub rentals.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions are necessary that, through the revision of taxation, prices can be regulated.
Looking at the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in Brianza area, they serve approximately 450 euros; for a single room from a minimum of 650 (Bande Nere area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 (in Victoria area).
In Florence a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas near the University, they serve 250/280 euros for a bed in a double room and from 370 to 500 for a single.
In Rome in the central areas near the University (San Lorenzo, Bologna Square) you ask about 600 euros for a single room and 450 for a bed in a double room.
Only slightly lower values (550 euros for a single room) in areas near other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You save only if you change peripheral area: 300 euros for a bed and 450 for a single room in Prenestina area, Centocelle and surroundings.
In Naples for a bed you are served 300/450 euros, for a room is spent from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari for a bed they serve 250/350 euro, at least 350 for an individual.
in the smaller cities the prices are lower in absolute terms, but it has a greater weight in the economy of the city.
In cities such as Perugia, where the phenomenon of rents to students and non-EU citizens is more frequent, there is a further anomaly: a 25/30% increase in the fee for foreign students compared to Italians.
Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso, the cities cancel the historic rooms
The historical cinemas close favoring multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas in a blind city is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the large Italian urban centers and also in provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticons on the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear almost always are historical places, full of memory, "it is as if a friend died, an acquaintance with whom one shared a piece of place and so much emotion", observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury at Cannes, which told the poetry of a provincial cinema and the nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that was always lost.
The figures given by Anec, the main association of merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay the most are mostly the cinemas of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 fewer cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for its disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, it is these three Italian regions that have registered the largest number of new cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it would be useful if new structures were built but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer to the meticons.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of traders: the previous state debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To support the sector it would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interesting the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that worried about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect the mono-room cinema both in the historic center and on the outskirts.
Among the planned rules there are mediated tax facilitation in favor of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the zone of limited traffic and will have special rates for parking.
'It is an initiative I like,' says Giuseppe Tornatore, 'and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example by setting up other measures.
It is true, that to contrast the extra power of the meticons, the traditional rooms have to improve the quality of the sound and the image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the cinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "New Cinema Paradiso", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side.
