When the energy is born of the waves, the great ones come down to the stage
It is an exterminated deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which the big ones like Chevron look.
The possibility of collecting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 70s along with the first oil crisis, investigations intensified.
When the price of oil was low, in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put aside, but now that environmental cases and the new rise in oil are giving the sector momentum.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated for 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electrical need could be covered by implants that exploit the movement of the sea waves.
This would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been Enersis, which in 2005 has sealed an agreement to build an implant in the North of Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away from betting on marine energy are more and more and among these companies have always voted for traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technology,” a spokesperson for a company associated with the US oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It is a pretty important sign, considering that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to carry out new drilling.
In addition to Chevron is Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to follow the path of energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, although not detailed indicate an increase in interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts speak of a technology still in its infancy, because there is no doubt that marine energy has a great environmental impact.
For now the impacts like those of the Portuguese or the Scots are small and do not seem to create major problems to the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, technology with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boas joined together.
The force of the waves, which causes the boas to move up and down, becomes hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure rotates a turbine which in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to the coast through submarine cables.
For now there are four implants of this type in development, pending only the federal approval, apart from the energy, could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a mall and a parking lot, using underwater turbines on New York’s East River.
The movement of the water when there are tides, rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotating movement that feeds the generator.
Verdant has said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Development of Electric Power, deserves at this time the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It’s mostly tidal energy that states like New York, Maine, and Alaska, along with others approaching the coast, have invested $7.5 million in 2008 and an investment of $35 million is planned for 2009.
